    <h1>Have Questions? Check Out Our Visionet BDD Framework FAQs: Setup & Version Control</h1>
    <img src="https://img.shields.io/badge/FAQs-Have%20questions%3F-006daf?logo=data:image/svg+xml;base64,"alt="FAQs">
    <h3>FAQ: Behavior-Driven Development (BDD) and Page Object Model (POM) with Cucumber and Selenium</h3>
        <h4>Q1: How do I structure feature files in a BDD framework?</h4>
    <p>A1: Feature files should be written in Gherkin syntax and organized by functionality or user story to make them easily understandable. Each feature file should contain scenarios that are descriptive and reflect user interactions with the application.</p>
    <h4>Q2: What are the best practices for writing step definitions in Cucumber?</h4>
    <p>A2: Keep step definitions concise and focused on a single action. Use annotations wisely to map steps in feature files to Java methods. Avoid writing assertions in step definitions; instead, call methods from page objects or helper classes.</p>
    <h4>Q3: How do I implement the Page Object Model with Selenium for better test maintainability?</h4>
    <p>A3: Implement POM by creating classes for each page of your application. Each class should encapsulate all possible interactions with the web page, and methods in these classes should return objects of other pages or the same page depending on the action.</p>
    <h4>FAQ: Running Tests with Maven and TestNG</h4>
    <h4>Q4: How do I run specific features or tags using Maven and TestNG?</h4>
    <p>A4: In your Maven pom.xml file, configure the TestNG suite xml file under the Surefire plugin. To run specific tags, include or exclude groups in your TestNG configuration file. For features, use the Cucumber options in your TestNG suite to specify paths to feature files.</p>
    <h4>Q5: What are the steps to execute a suite of tests in a Maven project?</h4>
    <p>A5: To run a suite, define your test suites in the testng.xml file. Then, execute the suite using the Maven command <code>mvn test</code> while specifying the TestNG suite file with <code>-Dsurefire.suiteXmlFiles=my_test_suite.xml</code>.</p>
    <h4>FAQ: Advanced Topics in Testing</h4>
    <h4>Q6: How can I integrate my testing framework with CI/CD pipelines?</h4>
    <p>A6: Use Maven to manage dependencies and test execution. Configure your CI/CD tool (like Jenkins, GitLab CI, or Azure DevOps) to trigger Maven commands. Set up webhooks in your source control to trigger tests on push or pull requests.</p>
    <h4>Q7: What are the benefits of using Selenium Grid for parallel test execution?</h4>
    <p>A7: Selenium Grid allows you to run tests in parallel across different browsers, versions, and operating systems, significantly reducing the time required for executing large test suites. It also helps in scaling your testing by distributing tests across multiple machines.</p>
    <h4>Q8: How do I implement custom TestNG listeners in my framework?</h4>
    <p>A8: Implement the TestNG ITestListener interface to create custom listeners. Define methods for different events like <code>onTestStart</code>, <code>onTestSuccess</code>, and <code>onTestFailure</code>. Add your listener to your tests by using the <code>@Listeners</code> annotation or by including it in your TestNG xml configuration.</p>
    <h4>FAQ: Git and Maven Setup for Visionet BDD Framework</h4>
    <h4>Q9: How do I install Git to manage the Visionet BDD Framework?</h4>
    <p>A9: Download and install Git from the official Git website. Follow the installation instructions provided on the site to set it up on your machine.</p>
    <h4>Q10: How do I clone the Visionet BDD Framework repository?</h4>
    <p>A10: Open your terminal or command prompt and execute the following command to clone the repository:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git clone https://github.com/DakshinaMoorthyPV/Visionet-BDD-Framework.git</pre>
    <h4>Q11: How do I navigate to the cloned project directory?</h4>
    <p>A11: After cloning the repository, use the command:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">cd Visionet-BDD-Framework</pre>
    <h4>Q12: How do I import the cloned Maven project into Eclipse?</h4>
    <p>A12: In Eclipse, go to <strong>File</strong> > <strong>Import...</strong>, select <strong>Maven</strong> > <strong>Existing Maven Projects</strong>, click <strong>Next</strong>, browse to the cloned directory, ensure the <em>pom.xml</em> file is selected, and click <strong>Finish</strong>.</p>
    <h4>Q13: How do I create and switch to a new branch in Git?</h4>
    <p>A13: To create a new branch and switch to it, run:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git checkout -b your-branch-name</pre>
    <h4>Q14: How do I push a new branch to the remote repository?</h4>
    <p>A14: After creating your branch, push it to the remote repository using:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git push -u origin your-branch-name</pre>
    <h4>Q15: How do I stage and commit changes in Git?</h4>
    <p>A15: Stage your changes with:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git add .</pre>
    <p>Then commit them by running:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git commit -m "Your commit message"</pre>
    <h4>Q16: How do I push committed changes to my branch?</h4>
    <p>A16: Push your changes to the remote repository with the command:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git push</pre>
    <h4>Q17: How do I merge my branch into the master branch?</h4>
    <p>A17: Switch to the master branch using:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git checkout master</pre>
    <p>Pull the latest changes with:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git pull origin master</pre>
    <p>Then merge your branch with:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git merge your-branch-name</pre>
    <h4>Q18: How do I handle merge conflicts in Git?</h4>
    <p>A18: If merge conflicts arise, manually edit the conflicted files to resolve them, then stage the changes with:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git add .</pre>
    <p>Continue the merge process by committing with:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git commit</pre>
    <h4>Q19: How do I push merged changes to the remote master branch?</h4>
    <p>A19: After resolving any conflicts and completing the merge, push the updated master branch to the remote repository with:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git push origin master</pre>
    <h4>Q20: How do I pull the latest changes from the master branch to my branch?</h4>
    <p>A20: To update your branch with the latest changes from the master, switch to your branch with:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git checkout your-branch-name</pre>
    <p>And pull the changes using:</p>
    <pre style="background-color: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px;">git pull origin master</pre>
